## Key Findings

### Finding 1: Strong Support for Telehealth, Despite Challenges

**78% of respondents** said they want to continue using telehealth for appropriate appointments.

Top reasons for telehealth preference:
1. "Don't have to drive to VA facility" (67%)
2. "Can attend from comfort of home" (54%)
3. "Saves time overall" (49%)
4. "Easier to fit into my schedule" (41%)
5. "Health conditions make travel difficult" (38%)

> "At 82 years old, I shouldn't have to drive 90 minutes each way just for a 15-minute check-up. Video visits have been a blessing when they work." — Army Veteran, Rural Montana

### Finding 2: Technical Difficulties Remain Pervasive

**61% of respondents** experienced technical difficulties with at least one telehealth appointment.

Most common issues reported:
| Issue | Percentage |
|-------|------------|
| Audio problems (can't hear or be heard) | 47% |
| Video not working | 38% |
| Couldn't figure out how to join | 34% |
| Got kicked out of appointment | 28% |
| Link didn't work | 24% |
| Long wait time in "virtual waiting room" | 21% |

> "I'm a combat veteran. I've faced enemy fire. But trying to get my camera to work for a doctor's appointment makes me want to give up." — Marine Veteran, Florida

### Finding 3: Significant Reliance on Caregiver Support

**44% of respondents** said they needed help from a family member, caregiver, or friend to connect to their telehealth appointment.

Among respondents age 75+, this number rises to **68%**.

Types of help needed:
- Setting up device/camera (52%)
- Clicking the right link to join (47%)
- Troubleshooting when something went wrong (61%)
- Staying in the appointment (adjusting settings, etc.) (29%)

> "My daughter has to come over every time I have a video appointment. She shouldn't have to take off work just to help me click a button." — Navy Veteran, Ohio

### Finding 4: Pre-Appointment Preparation is Inadequate

**Only 34%** of respondents said they received clear instructions on how to prepare for their telehealth appointment.

**89%** said they would use a tool to test their setup before appointments if it were easy to find.

Respondents who tested their setup beforehand (through any means) were **3x more likely** to rate their telehealth experience as "excellent."

### Finding 5: Significant Age-Based Disparities

Veterans over 70 reported **2x more technical challenges** than Veterans under 60.

| Experience | Under 60 | 60-70 | Over 70 |
|------------|----------|-------|---------|
| Joined without difficulty | 71% | 54% | 38% |
| Needed help to connect | 22% | 41% | 68% |
| Missed appointment due to tech | 8% | 14% | 27% |
| Would prefer in-person instead | 18% | 29% | 44% |

### Finding 6: Rural Veterans Face Compounded Challenges

Rural Veterans reported:
- Lower internet reliability (34% reported issues vs. 12% urban)
- Fewer options for in-person technical help
- Greater appreciation for telehealth (82% support vs. 74% urban)
- More frustration when technical issues occur

> "Out here, the nearest VA is 3 hours away. Telehealth is my only realistic option. When it doesn't work, I just don't get care that week." — Army Veteran, Rural Nevada

